# Data Layer Conventions

## Three Layers

```
src/lib/
├── data/         ← Static JS arrays/objects — imported directly by Server Components
├── api/          ← Async fetchers — server-only, may call DB or external APIs
└── validations/  ← Zod schemas — shared by forms (client) and route handlers (server)
```

---

## `lib/data/` — Static Data

Plain JS files. No React. No JSX. No async. Export named arrays or objects.

```js
// src/lib/data/products.js

export const products = [
  {
    id: 1,
    slug: 'smart-transformer-x200',
    name: 'Smart Transformer X200',
    category: 'transformers',
    summary: 'AI-powered transformer monitoring system.',
    images: ['/images/products/transformer-x200-1.jpg'],
    // ...
  },
]
```

Rules:
- No inline JSX or SVG — icons belong in `public/icons/` or imported in the component
- No `import React` — these are pure data files
- No async functions — if you need to fetch, use `lib/api/` instead
- Export named constants, not default exports

---

## `lib/api/` — Server-Only Fetchers

Every file MUST start with `import 'server-only'`. This causes a build error if any Client Component accidentally imports it — protecting secrets and server logic.

```js
// src/lib/api/products.js
import 'server-only'

import { products as staticProducts } from '@/lib/data/products'

export async function getProducts() {
  // Currently returns static data — swap for DB/API call later without touching components
  return staticProducts
}

export async function getProductBySlug(slug) {
  const product = staticProducts.find((p) => p.slug === slug)
  return product ?? null
}
```

Rules:
- ALWAYS `import 'server-only'` on line 1
- NEVER import in a `"use client"` component
- May access `process.env.SECRET_*` variables
- Functions must be async (even if currently returning static data — prepares for API swap)
- Return `null` instead of throwing when an item is not found; let the page call `notFound()`

---

## `lib/validations/` — Zod Schemas

Schemas are shared between the frontend form and the API route handler.

```js
// src/lib/validations/contact.schema.js
import { z } from 'zod'

export const contactSchema = z.object({
  name:    z.string().min(2, 'Name must be at least 2 characters'),
  email:   z.string().email('Invalid email address'),
  phone:   z.string().optional(),
  subject: z.string().min(5, 'Subject must be at least 5 characters'),
  message: z.string().min(20, 'Message must be at least 20 characters'),
})
```

Usage in API route handler (server):
```js
// app/api/contact/route.js
import { contactSchema } from '@/lib/validations/contact.schema'

const parsed = contactSchema.safeParse(body)
if (!parsed.success) {
  return NextResponse.json({ error: parsed.error.flatten() }, { status: 422 })
}
```

Usage in form (client):
```js
// features/contact/ContactForm.jsx
import { zodResolver } from '@hookform/resolvers/zod'
import { contactSchema } from '@/lib/validations/contact.schema'

const { register, handleSubmit } = useForm({ resolver: zodResolver(contactSchema) })
```

---

## API Route Handlers

```js
// app/api/contact/route.js
import { NextResponse } from 'next/server'
import { contactSchema } from '@/lib/validations/contact.schema'
import { sendContactEmail } from '@/lib/api/contact'

export async function POST(req) {
  try {
    const body = await req.json()
    const parsed = contactSchema.safeParse(body)

    if (!parsed.success) {
      return NextResponse.json(
        { error: parsed.error.flatten() },
        { status: 422 }
      )
    }

    await sendContactEmail(parsed.data)
    return NextResponse.json({ success: true }, { status: 200 })

  } catch (err) {
    console.error('[POST /api/contact]', err)
    return NextResponse.json({ error: 'Internal server error' }, { status: 500 })
  }
}
```

Rules:
- Always validate with Zod before processing
- Always wrap in try/catch
- Never expose error stack traces in the response body
- Only export HTTP method functions (`GET`, `POST`, `PUT`, `DELETE`, `PATCH`)
